<article>
    <h1>Top 5 laksa</h1>
    <h2>1 328 Ka&#xAD;tong Laksa</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201213/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-13"><time>2020-12-13</time></a>
        - <span>FRONT PAGE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Main branch: 216 East Coast Road</p>
    <p>Open: 9am to 9pm daily Price: $5.50 and $7.50</p>
    <p>This is the place to go for Ka­tong laksa and it is do­ing so well that it has six out­lets, in­clud­ing two in East Coast Road alone.</p>
    <p>It gets my vote be­cause of the metic­u­lous at­ten­tion paid to en­sure I en­joy ev­ery bite of the dish.</p>
    <p>For ex­am­ple, even though the gravy is creamy with co­conut milk, it is not so rich that I can­not drink up ev­ery drop.</p>
    <p>A sig­na­ture of Ka­tong laksa is that the dish comes with just a spoon – no chop­sticks – so that the diner can savour the noo­dles to­gether with the gravy and other in­gre­di­ents.</p>
    <p>The thick bee­hoon is cut into short strands and the fish­cake is juli­enned to fit eas­ily in the spoon.</p>
    <p>There is no bean­curd puff or taupok, though I think that would work too if juli­enned.</p>
    <p>But you do get plump and juicy cock­les, which are de­li­cious with the spicy broth.</p>
    <p>The bowl comes with a sa­chet of sam­bal to add to the noo­dles if you need more heat. But I find it changes the pro­file of the gravy, mak­ing it sweeter and giv­ing it a strong dried-shrimp fla­vor.</p>
    <p>I pre­fer it unadul­ter­ated with its fra­grant aroma of co­conut milk.</p>

